Another option is to use the `URIComponentsBuilder` as a `URIBuilder`.

The reason you would want to use the `build(Object...)` even without parameters is that it returns a `URI` rather than `URIComponents`.

But the only reason `URIComponentsBuilder` has this method is because it implements `URIBuilder`, which means you can use it as a `URIBuilder`, like this:

```
public class JustATest {

    public static void main(String[] args) {
        UriBuilder builder = UriComponentsBuilder.fromHttpUrl(&quot;http://example.com/foo/bar/baz&quot;);
        builder.port(8088);
        URI uri = builder.build();
        System.out.println(uri);

    }
}
```
So in this example I am creating a builder for a certain URL then changing its port. But that doesn&#39;t matter, the point is that I am assigning the `UriComponentsBuilder` to a variable of type `UriBuilder`. As such, it only recognizes the varargs `build(Object...)`, and so you don&#39;t need to use anything as parameter.

